WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.220
The human digestive system consists of two major parts: the gastrointestinal — GI — tract and the accessory organs.

00:00:04.220 --> 00:00:05.850


00:00:05.850 --> 00:00:09.250


00:00:09.250 --> 00:00:12.000
The GI tract begins with the oral cavity, which houses the tongue, teeth, and salivary glands.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.340


00:00:16.340 --> 00:00:20.040
The mouth mechanically breaks down food and initiates carbohydrate digestion.

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:22.310


00:00:22.310 --> 00:00:25.430
The pharynx is a muscular tube behind the mouth that helps propel the chewed food to the esophagus.

00:00:25.430 --> 00:00:29.250


00:00:29.250 --> 00:00:31.920
The esophagus transports food to the stomach through rhythmic contractions called peristalsis.

00:00:31.920 --> 00:00:35.650


00:00:35.650 --> 00:00:38.620
The stomach is located below the diaphragm.

00:00:38.620 --> 00:00:41.400
It stores and churns food and aids in the enzymatic breakdown of proteins.

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:44.420


00:00:44.420 --> 00:00:48.230
The small intestine is a coiled tube in the central and lower abdomen.

00:00:48.230 --> 00:00:49.190


00:00:49.190 --> 00:00:54.120
It is responsible for nutrient absorption and fat digestion.

00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:58.420
The large intestine, or colon, follows the small intestine.

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:03.110
It absorbs water, electrolytes, and vitamins and houses beneficial gut bacteria.

00:01:03.110 --> 00:01:05.450


00:01:05.450 --> 00:01:07.930
The anus is the terminal part of the rectum, involved in eliminating waste.

00:01:07.930 --> 00:01:10.620


00:01:10.620 --> 00:01:15.090
The accessory digestive organs include the liver, pancreas, and gallbladder.

00:01:15.090 --> 00:01:17.540


00:01:17.540 --> 00:01:19.000
